---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, allPaths, appBySlug, appPairs, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const slug = Astro.params.slug || '';
const path = Array.isArray(slug) ? slug.join('/') : slug;
const parts = path.split('/').filter(Boolean);
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
function channelApps(){ return APPS.filter((app) => app.channels.includes(site.channel) || app.channels.includes('marketing')); }
const valid = allPaths().includes(path);
if (!valid) return Astro.redirect('/');
const pairs = appPairs();
const primaryApps = channelApps().slice(0, 12);
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={`/${path}`}>
  <section class="border-b border-[#24170f]/10 py-14">
    <div class="container grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_320px] lg:items-end">
      <div>
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Shopify email app file</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-4 !text-5xl md:!text-7xl">{title}</h1>
        <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">{desc} This page is written for merchants comparing email software against real operating constraints: list growth, customer history, discount discipline, margin, deliverability, and the amount of weekly attention the app will require after the first setup call.</p>
      </div>
      <aside class="ledger-card">
        <div class="text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[#9a5b16]">How to read this page</div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-[#4a2d17]">A good Shopify email app does three things at once: it captures intent, turns order history into better timing, and keeps campaigns from colliding with each other. If a tool only makes broadcast newsletters easier, it is not enough for a retention-focused store.</p>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && !parts[1] && (
    <section class="container py-12">
      <div class="mb-8 max-w-4xl">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Rankings</p>
        <h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-black tracking-tight">Best Shopify email apps, ranked by merchant workload</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">The ranking favors tools that help a Shopify store build durable lifecycle revenue. That means product-aware flows, customer-stage segmentation, clean suppression rules, useful reporting, and enough guidance that a small team can improve the program without hiring an agency for every change.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
        {APPS.map((app, i) => (
          <a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3"><span class="rank-pill">{i + 1}</span><span class="text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-[#9a5b16]">{app.category}</span></div>
            <h2 class="mt-4 text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">{app.name}</h2>
            <p class="mt-3 text-[#5d3a1d]">Best for {app.bestFor}. The important question is whether this app gives your team a clearer weekly operating rhythm, not whether it has the longest feature checklist.</p>
            <p class="mt-4 text-sm font-black">{app.pricing}</p>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>
  )}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => {
    const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!;
    return (
      <section class="container grid gap-8 py-12 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_340px]">
        <article class="prose-shopify card">
          <h2>What {app.name} actually has to solve for Shopify stores</h2>
          <p>{app.shopifyFit} The useful way to evaluate {app.name} is not to ask whether it can send an email. Almost every tool can do that. The better question is whether it can take Shopify context — products viewed, collections purchased, discount behavior, checkout events, refund history, fulfillment timing, subscriptions, and customer lifetime value — and turn that context into decisions a merchant can trust.</p>
          <p>For a store comparing {app.name} against other Shopify email apps, the first checkpoint is the first week after install. Can the team connect the store, import subscribers safely, identify existing customers, create the core lifecycle flows, and avoid sending awkward emails to people who just purchased? A tool that feels powerful in a demo but slows down during setup will often produce less revenue than a simpler system that gets the important customer moments live quickly.</p>
          <h2>Where {app.name} fits best</h2>
          <p>{app.name} is strongest for {app.bestFor}. That does not mean every merchant in that category should choose it blindly. The app should match the store’s operating model. A founder-led brand may need practical guidance and fast editing. A larger retention team may need deeper segmentation, experimentation, and governance. A store with thousands of SKUs may care more about catalog logic than a store with ten hero products. A subscription-heavy brand needs timing rules that understand replenishment, skips, cancellations, and upcoming renewals.</p>
          <p>When {app.name} is a good fit, it should make the next ninety days of work easier: capture more qualified subscribers, welcome them with the right proof, recover carts without over-discounting, educate first-time buyers, time the second purchase, and win back customers before the list goes cold. If those jobs still require spreadsheets, manual exports, or constant agency help, the app is not carrying enough of the Shopify email burden.</p>
          <h2>Strengths to notice in a real evaluation</h2>
          <ul>{app.strengths.map((strength) => <li>{strength}</li>)}</ul>
          <p>The strongest parts of {app.name} matter most when they reduce weekly decision fatigue. Good Shopify email execution is not only creative; it is operational. Someone has to decide which segments deserve a campaign, which customers should be suppressed, what offer is safe for margin, whether a buyer should enter a replenishment path, and how to interpret revenue that may have happened anyway. An app earns its place when it makes those calls easier to manage.</p>
          <h2>Limits and buying risks</h2>
          <ul>{app.limits.map((limit) => <li>{limit}</li>)}</ul>
          <p>The common mistake is buying the most famous platform and assuming the program will improve by itself. The second mistake is buying the cheapest sender and discovering that the missing segmentation costs more than the subscription. Before choosing {app.name}, rebuild a sample welcome flow, cart flow, post-purchase flow, and winback flow on paper. Mark every rule that depends on Shopify data. If the app cannot express those rules cleanly, the team will eventually work around the system instead of using it.</p>
          <h2>Shopify buying advice</h2>
          <p>Choose {app.name} if its workflow depth matches your next stage of retention work. Skip it if your team only needs a one-off newsletter sender, if pricing forces you to suppress useful segmentation, or if the tool makes basic Shopify lifecycle moments feel like engineering projects. The best Shopify email app is the one your team will operate every week: reviewing segments, updating creative, testing offers, and protecting deliverability before a promotion goes out.</p>
          <p>For most growing stores, the practical shortlist should include Sequenzy for agent-first lifecycle execution, Klaviyo for deep ecommerce data, and one simpler option if the team values speed over breadth. The final decision should come from a workflow test, not a feature matrix. If the app helps you launch better customer journeys with less hesitation, it deserves the budget. If it adds dashboards without improving the next send, keep looking.</p>
        </article>
        <aside class="card h-fit">
          <div class="text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[#9a5b16]">Snapshot</div>
          <dl class="mt-5 space-y-4 text-sm text-[#4a2d17]"><div><dt class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Category</dt><dd>{app.category}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Pricing</dt><dd>{app.pricing}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Best for</dt><dd>{app.bestFor}</dd></div></dl>
          <a class="btn btn-primary mt-7 w-full" href="https://sequenzy.com">Compare with Sequenzy</a>
        </aside>
      </section>
    );
  })()}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && !parts[1] && (
    <section class="container py-12"><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{pairs.map(([a, b]) => <a class="card" href={`/compare/${a.slug}-vs-${b.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black">{a.name} vs {b.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#5d3a1d]">A practical buying comparison for Shopify email teams deciding which workflow is easier to operate.</p></a>)}</div></section>
  )}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => {
    const [a, b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug);
    return (
      <section class="container py-12">
        <div class="card overflow-x-auto"><table class="data-table"><thead><tr><th>Criteria</th><th>{a?.name}</th><th>{b?.name}</th><th>Merchant takeaway</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Best fit</td><td>{a?.bestFor}</td><td>{b?.bestFor}</td><td>Pick based on the retention operating model, not the louder brand.</td></tr><tr><td>Pricing pressure</td><td>{a?.pricing}</td><td>{b?.pricing}</td><td>Model cost against profile growth, list hygiene, and revenue per recipient.</td></tr><tr><td>Primary strength</td><td>{a?.strengths[0]}</td><td>{b?.strengths[0]}</td><td>Choose the strength that removes the biggest blocker in your current email program.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
        <article class="prose-shopify mt-8 card">
          <h2>Verdict for Shopify email teams</h2>
          <p>{a?.name} is usually better when the store needs {a?.bestFor}. {b?.name} is stronger when the team cares more about {b?.bestFor}. That difference sounds simple, but it changes the daily work inside a Shopify retention program. One tool may make segmentation easier. Another may make setup faster. Another may have better agency support. The right answer is the app that improves your highest-value customer moments first.</p>
          <p>Run the comparison through four flows before committing: welcome, abandoned cart, post-purchase, and winback. For each flow, ask whether the app can use Shopify purchase history, product context, customer status, consent, and discount behavior without manual exports. Then ask whether a non-technical marketer can update the logic during a sale week. If a tool wins the demo but loses that workflow test, it will probably slow the store down after implementation.</p>
          <p>If both tools feel close, choose the one that creates better operating habits. A Shopify email program compounds when the team reviews flows, tests offers, refreshes product blocks, suppresses customers intelligently, and watches deliverability. It stalls when every change feels risky. That is why this comparison favors clarity, lifecycle control, and practical weekly use over broad feature claims.</p>
        </article>
      </section>
    );
  })()}

  {parts[0] === 'for' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{SEGMENTS.map((segment) => <a class="card" href={`/for/${segment.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black">{segment.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#5d3a1d]">Selection pressure: {segment.pain}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const segment = SEGMENTS.find((item) => item.slug === parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>How {segment.name} should choose Shopify email apps</h2><p>{segment.name} have to account for {segment.pain}. That changes the app shortlist because the best email software is not always the biggest platform. The right app is the one that can turn this store’s buying cycle into useful customer timing.</p><p>A store in this category should start by listing the customer moments that create real margin. Some subscribers need education before a first purchase. Some buyers need reassurance after checkout. Some customers need replenishment reminders, sizing help, bundle suggestions, launch access, or a reason to return after a seasonal spike. The email app should make those moments easy to build and easy to revise.</p><p>The recommended shortlist is deliberately practical. {primaryApps.slice(0, 7).map((app) => app.name).join(', ')} all solve part of the problem, but the best choice depends on whether the team values guided lifecycle execution, ecommerce data depth, low setup friction, or multichannel coverage. Do not buy the platform until someone has mapped the top three revenue flows and confirmed that the app can express them cleanly.</p><h2>Recommended shortlist</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0, 7).map((app) => <li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>{app.name}</a> — {app.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Implementation notes</h2><p>Start with one money flow, one trust-building flow, and one reactivation flow. The money flow should recover immediate intent. The trust flow should make new buyers more confident. The reactivation flow should bring back customers before paid acquisition has to replace them. More campaigns are not automatically better; better timing and cleaner suppression usually beat extra sends.</p></article></section>; })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{USE_CASES.map((useCase) => <a class="card" href={`/use-cases/${useCase.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black">{useCase.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#5d3a1d]">Use Shopify email apps to {useCase.job}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const useCase = USE_CASES.find((item) => item.slug === parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Best Shopify email app approach for {useCase.name}</h2><p>The job of {useCase.name} is to {useCase.job}. For Shopify email apps, that means using store events, product context, consent, purchase history, and customer stage to decide who gets the message and when. A weak setup treats the flow as a generic autoresponder. A stronger setup treats it as a merchandising decision with timing, exclusions, proof, and measurement.</p><p>The app should make the flow easy to operate without constant rebuilds. A merchant should be able to adjust the offer, exclude recent buyers, feature relevant products, pause the flow during a major sale, and understand whether the revenue is incremental. If those tasks require exports or developer help, the flow will not improve often enough.</p><h2>Apps to consider</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0, 8).map((app) => <li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>{app.name}</a>: {app.shopifyFit}</li>)}</ul><h2>What to measure</h2><p>Measure recovered revenue, unsubscribe rate, repeat purchase rate, margin after discounts, and revenue by segment. Avoid judging {useCase.name} only by opens or attributed clicks. The best flow is the one that changes customer behavior without training the list to wait for a coupon.</p></article></section>; })()}

  {parts[0] === 'alternatives' && (() => { const app = appBySlug((parts[1] || '').replace('-alternative', ''))!; const alternatives = APPS.filter((item) => item.slug !== app.slug).slice(0, 8); return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Why Shopify stores look for {app.name} alternatives</h2><p>{app.name} is a credible option, but it is not always the right fit for every Shopify store. Common reasons to compare alternatives include pricing, migration workload, segmentation depth, reporting clarity, support expectations, and how much guidance the team wants when building lifecycle email. The goal is not to switch for novelty. The goal is to find the app that makes the next stage of retention easier to run.</p><p>Before choosing an alternative, document what is actually broken. If the current tool is too expensive, model cost at the next subscriber milestone. If segmentation is the issue, list the exact Shopify events and customer fields the team cannot use. If the team is not launching campaigns, decide whether the blocker is strategy, interface complexity, or lack of ownership. Different alternatives solve different problems.</p><h2>Best alternatives</h2><ul>{alternatives.map((alternative) => <li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${alternative.slug}`}>{alternative.name}</a> — {alternative.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Selection rule</h2><p>Do not switch tools just for a cleaner interface. Switch when the alternative makes an important Shopify workflow easier to launch, easier to measure, or cheaper to scale. A successful migration should leave the store with fewer manual steps, clearer customer journeys, and a stronger weekly email rhythm.</p></article></section>; })()}

  {parts[0] === 'guides' && <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Shopify email app selection framework</h2><p>Pick a Shopify email app by matching your business model to lifecycle jobs. New stores need capture, welcome, cart recovery, and first purchase campaigns. Growing stores need segmentation, post-purchase education, replenishment, winback, and deliverability discipline. Larger brands need governance, experimentation, attribution, and channel coordination. The wrong app makes those jobs feel like separate projects. The right app turns them into a manageable operating system.</p><p>The first question is how much help the team needs deciding what to send. Some tools are powerful databases with blank canvases. Others are lighter campaign senders. Sequenzy is strongest when the merchant wants agent-first lifecycle guidance and fast execution. Klaviyo is strongest when the merchant wants deep ecommerce data and has the discipline to manage it. Omnisend is strongest when the team wants email, SMS, and push without enterprise complexity. Those are different buying reasons, not interchangeable labels.</p><p>The second question is whether the app respects Shopify reality. Stores have inventory constraints, discounts that affect margin, fulfillment delays, one-time gift buyers, subscriptions, bundles, refunds, and customers who should be suppressed from certain campaigns. If an app cannot use that context, it will create blunt campaigns. Blunt campaigns can still make money, but they usually do it by sending more often or discounting harder than necessary.</p><p>The third question is weekly ownership. A retention program improves when someone reviews flow performance, refreshes creative, tests offers, checks deliverability, and adjusts segments. If the app is too complicated for that weekly loop, performance will decay. Choose the platform your team can keep operating after the excitement of migration ends.</p><h2>Internal linking map</h2><ul><li><a class="link" href="/apps">All app reviews</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/compare">Comparison hub</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart guide</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/for/fashion">Fashion store guide</a></li></ul></article></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Detailed operating playbook for {app.name}</h2><p>A serious review of {app.name} has to move beyond feature labels and ask how the platform behaves when a Shopify store is busy, messy, and under margin pressure. The first month should not be spent decorating newsletters. It should be spent proving that the app can identify subscribers correctly, understand who has purchased before, respect consent, read product intent, and keep customers from entering conflicting flows. This is where many email tools look similar in screenshots but feel very different in production.</p><p>Start the evaluation with four sample customers: a brand-new subscriber who has never purchased, a cart abandoner with a discount code already attached, a first-time buyer waiting for fulfillment, and a customer whose last order suggests replenishment or replacement timing. Walk each person through {app.name}. The best Shopify email apps make the next message obvious and make the exclusion rules visible. If the team has to export data, create manual tags, or guess whether another automation will fire, the app is adding operational risk.</p><p>For {app.name}, the buying conversation should also include creative ownership. Shopify email performance depends on product blocks, social proof, offer framing, timing, and plain language. A strong platform lets a marketer update those pieces without breaking logic. It should be easy to swap products for a collection, hide out-of-stock items, change a discount rule for VIP customers, and pause a flow during a major campaign. When those small edits require a specialist, the store gradually stops improving the program.</p><p>Measurement is another deciding factor. Revenue attribution is useful, but it can over-credit emails that would have received the order anyway. Review {app.name} by looking at repeat purchase rate, time to second order, unsubscribes, spam complaints, deliverability, margin after incentives, and performance by customer stage. A flow that increases orders while teaching every buyer to wait for 20% off is not healthy retention. The app should help the merchant see that tradeoff before the discount habit becomes permanent.</p><p>The final question is whether {app.name} makes weekly email work lighter or heavier. A practical operating rhythm includes one performance review, one creative refresh, one segmentation improvement, and one deliverability check each week. If the tool turns those jobs into a manageable checklist, it can compound. If it hides the next action behind dashboards and vague campaign reports, the store may still pay for software while the lifecycle program stays shallow.</p></article></section>; })()}
  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>How to run a real {a?.name} vs {b?.name} workflow test</h2><p>The cleanest way to compare {a?.name} and {b?.name} is to ignore the sales deck for one hour and rebuild the same Shopify lifecycle in both systems. Choose a welcome series, an abandoned cart flow, a post-purchase education sequence, and a winback path. Then document the trigger, audience, exclusions, offer logic, product data, reporting view, and the person on the team who could edit it next month. The winner is the tool that makes those details clear without forcing a workaround.</p><p>{a?.name} may look stronger on one dimension while {b?.name} wins another. That is why the decision should start with the store’s next bottleneck. If the list is growing but first purchase rate is weak, welcome and education matter most. If checkout intent is leaking, cart recovery rules and discount discipline matter. If first-time buyers are not returning, post-purchase and replenishment timing should dominate the evaluation. A generic scorecard hides these differences.</p><p>Pricing should be modeled against real customer growth, not today’s subscriber count. Shopify stores often add profiles during seasonal campaigns, giveaways, product launches, and paid acquisition pushes. The better app is not always cheaper at signup; it is the one whose cost still makes sense when segments, suppressions, and customer value are included. Also count team time. A platform that costs less but requires constant manual cleanup may be the expensive choice.</p><p>Data depth is the other swing factor. The comparison should ask whether each tool can see products purchased, collections viewed, order count, discount history, fulfillment status, gift behavior, subscription state, and engagement recency. Those fields shape the difference between useful lifecycle email and generic blasting. If either app cannot use the Shopify context that matters to the store, it should lose points even if it has a long integration list.</p><p>End the test by choosing the tool that will create better habits. Good email teams review performance, refresh creative, suppress customers carefully, test offers, and protect inbox placement. The right app makes those habits easier. The wrong app wins the demo and then makes every change feel risky. For most merchants, that operating difference matters more than another template library.</p></article></section>; })()}
  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const segment = SEGMENTS.find((item) => item.slug === parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Long-form email strategy for {segment.name}</h2><p>{segment.name} need email systems that understand why customers hesitate, how often they should return, and which proof makes the purchase feel safe. The pressure around {segment.pain} means a generic newsletter calendar will underperform. The store should design email around purchase moments: discovery, comparison, checkout, confirmation, use, replenishment or repeat purchase, and reactivation. Each moment needs different data and different copy.</p><p>For this category, the first implementation step is to map the catalog into useful decision groups. Products with short repeat cycles deserve different timing than gifts, premium items, limited drops, or bundles. The app should make it easy to segment by product purchased, collection interest, order value, size or variant behavior, subscription status, and last purchase date. Without those fields, the brand will send broad campaigns that feel convenient for the marketer rather than relevant to the shopper.</p><p>The welcome path should answer the biggest buying objection before introducing aggressive discounts. A new subscriber may need sizing guidance, ingredient education, style inspiration, routine advice, shipping clarity, warranty proof, or customer stories. The email app should let the merchant adapt that proof by source and interest. Someone who joined from a product page is not the same as someone who joined from a giveaway. Treating them the same wastes attention.</p><p>After the first order, {segment.name} should use email to reduce anxiety and set up the next purchase. Confirmation, fulfillment, education, care instructions, community proof, and review requests can all protect retention. The sequence should not immediately push another coupon unless the product category supports that behavior. The goal is to create confidence and habit, not only another attributed click.</p><p>When evaluating Shopify email apps for this store type, prioritize the platform that makes this operating rhythm simple: weekly segment review, monthly creative refresh, quarterly flow audit, and sale-period suppression checks. A store dealing with {segment.pain} cannot afford a system that forces every improvement into a custom project. It needs an email tool that turns category knowledge into repeatable lifecycle work.</p></article></section>; })()}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const useCase = USE_CASES.find((item) => item.slug === parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Full execution plan for {useCase.name}</h2><p>{useCase.name} should be treated as a commercial system, not a single email. The job is to {useCase.job}, which means the app must combine trigger accuracy, customer context, offer control, creative proof, and measurement. A weak setup fires because a timer elapsed. A strong setup fires because the customer entered a meaningful Shopify state and the message helps them take the next step.</p><p>Begin with the trigger. Decide exactly what qualifies someone for the flow, how long the app should wait, and which customers should never enter. Recent buyers, support cases, gift purchasers, subscription customers, VIPs, discount-only shoppers, and people already in another high-priority automation may need different treatment. The best Shopify email apps make those exclusions visible enough that a marketer can audit them before a busy sale period.</p><p>Next define the message architecture. The first email should usually solve the immediate hesitation: trust, product fit, timing, checkout friction, education, or reminder value. A second email can add proof, comparison help, or a softer offer. A third email should only exist if it adds something new. Many stores damage deliverability by adding extra emails that repeat the same discount. The better approach is to let customer behavior determine whether the flow continues.</p><p>Product context is what separates Shopify-specific email from generic automation. For {useCase.name}, the app should understand which item, collection, price point, or prior order created the opportunity. Dynamic product blocks are useful only if they are accurate, in stock, and aligned with the customer’s interest. If the app cannot maintain that connection, the flow will eventually send awkward recommendations or stale offers.</p><p>Measurement should include more than the dashboard’s attributed revenue number. Review incremental orders, margin after discounts, unsubscribe rate, spam complaints, conversion by segment, second-order behavior, and whether the flow changes paid acquisition efficiency. A use case is successful when it improves the customer journey and can keep running without constant rescue. Choose the app that makes that kind of disciplined operation realistic.</p></article></section>; })()}
  {parts[0] === 'alternatives' && (() => { const app = appBySlug((parts[1] || '').replace('-alternative', ''))!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Migration checklist when replacing {app.name}</h2><p>Looking for {app.name} alternatives should start with a precise diagnosis. A Shopify store may be unhappy because costs rose, because segmentation is too hard, because deliverability slipped, because reporting is confusing, or because the team never built the flows that were promised during implementation. Each problem points to a different alternative. Switching without naming the problem usually recreates the same weak lifecycle program in a new interface.</p><p>Before migration, inventory every live email asset: forms, welcome flows, cart and checkout flows, browse abandonment, post-purchase, replenishment, winback, loyalty, review requests, VIP campaigns, discount codes, suppression segments, and transactional-adjacent messages. Mark which pieces actually create value and which exist because nobody wanted to delete them. The alternative should not inherit clutter by default.</p><p>Data portability matters. Confirm how contacts, consent timestamps, suppression status, order history, tags, custom properties, and engagement events will move. A cheaper or simpler app can become risky if it loses the context that keeps emails relevant. Shopify merchants should also test whether historical purchasers are identified correctly after the move; duplicate customer records can distort segmentation and reporting.</p><p>Run the new platform in a staged way. Rebuild one high-value flow first and compare the output against {app.name}: who qualifies, who is excluded, what product data appears, how discounts are generated, and how revenue is reported. Then migrate the next flow only after the team trusts the result. This slower approach protects revenue and prevents the store from discovering problems during a launch week.</p><p>The best alternative is the one that fixes the operating constraint, not the one with the loudest promise. If the store needs strategy, choose guidance. If it needs data depth, choose Shopify-native segmentation. If it needs speed, choose a workflow the team will actually use. A successful move leaves the merchant with cleaner flows, fewer manual steps, and a clearer weekly email rhythm than {app.name} provided.</p></article></section>; })()}
  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Final buyer notes for {a?.name} and {b?.name}</h2><p>Before a merchant chooses between these tools, the team should write a one-page operating brief. List the flows that must be live in the first thirty days, the customer fields each flow needs, the discount rules that protect margin, and the reporting questions leadership will ask after launch. Then score {a?.name} and {b?.name} against that brief instead of against abstract popularity.</p><p>Also include a failure rehearsal. Imagine deliverability drops, a promotion overlaps with a post-purchase flow, inventory sells out, or a VIP segment receives the wrong coupon. Which app makes the problem easier to diagnose and repair? Shopify email tools are not only judged when campaigns go well. They are judged when a busy store needs to make a safe edit quickly.</p></article></section>; })()}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const useCase = USE_CASES.find((item) => item.slug === parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Operational safeguards for {useCase.name}</h2><p>The last step is quality control. Preview the flow with real customer examples before turning it loose. Confirm that a recent purchaser is excluded, that products are available, that discount language matches the code, that mobile formatting is readable, and that the unsubscribe path is clear. Small QA work prevents the kind of awkward email that makes customers question the brand.</p><p>After launch, schedule a review rather than waiting for a crisis. Look at who entered, who converted, who unsubscribed, and which customers received overlapping campaigns. Then improve one rule or one message at a time. The best Shopify email apps make that iterative loop ordinary, which is why they create durable value long after the first flow goes live.</p></article></section>; })()}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>{app.name} evaluation worksheet: examples, risks, and proof</h2><p>Use this worksheet with real Shopify examples instead of demo data. Create four customers before the buying meeting: a new subscriber from a discount popup, a shopper who abandoned a cart with two products from different collections, a first-time buyer waiting for fulfillment, and a repeat buyer whose last order suggests replenishment. Score {app.name} by whether each profile enters the right journey, receives the right product context, and avoids the wrong coupon. This exposes the difference between a polished editor and an email system that can operate a live store.</p><p>Implementation should move in a controlled sequence. First connect Shopify, import consent, and check duplicate customer handling. Then rebuild welcome, abandoned cart, post-purchase, replenishment or winback, and only then migrate newsletters. For each flow, write the trigger, delay, exclusions, offer, product block, fallback copy, owner, and review date. If {app.name} cannot make those choices visible, the team will eventually rely on memory during launch weeks, which is how overlapping discounts and awkward post-purchase emails happen.</p><p>Migration risk is not only technical. It includes lost consent timestamps, missing suppression lists, broken dynamic product blocks, inaccurate revenue attribution, outdated discounts, and a team that does not know which dashboard is now the source of truth. Protect the move by running {app.name} against a small segment first, comparing who qualified with the old system, and checking actual Shopify orders before trusting the app's revenue report.</p><h3>Score {app.name} before signing</h3><ul><li><strong>9-10:</strong> clean Shopify identity, easy suppression, margin-aware offers, clear reporting, and weekly edits a marketer can own