  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Comparison scorecard: when {a?.name} wins and when {b?.name} wins</h2><p>Run the same Shopify scenario through both apps: a paid-social visitor joins a popup, browses a product, abandons checkout, buys after a reminder, receives education, and should be nudged toward a second purchase later. The better platform is the one that keeps the customer journey legible. You should be able to see the source, product context, purchase status, discount exposure, and next eligible message without stitching together spreadsheets.</p><p>{a?.name} should win points if it removes the store's current bottleneck with less maintenance. That might be guided lifecycle planning, deeper ecommerce data, faster templates, better agency support, or lower profile costs. {b?.name} should win when its strengths match the next ninety days more closely. A merchant preparing for a launch needs different controls than a merchant fixing deliverability or building replenishment for consumables.</p><p>Do not let pricing hide workload. Model list growth, seasonal imports, duplicate profiles, SMS or email volume, agency hours, discount cost, and reporting cleanup. Then run a failure rehearsal: inventory sells out, a post-purchase flow overlaps with a sale, a coupon leaks to VIPs, or deliverability drops before a promotion. Choose the app that makes the failure easier to diagnose and safer to repair.</p><h3>Practical decision rubric</h3><ul><li><strong>Data fit:</strong> can the app use product, order, discount, and customer-stage fields without manual tagging?</li><li><strong>Flow fit:</strong> can a marketer update welcome, cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and winback without breaking exclusions?</li><li><strong>Measurement fit:</strong> does reporting distinguish incremental behavior from revenue that would have happened anyway?</li><li><strong>Team fit:</strong> will the owner open the tool every week, or will it become an expensive archive of old flows?</li></ul></article></section>; })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const useCase = USE_CASES.find((item) => item.slug === parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Detailed build sheet for {useCase.name}</h2><p>Start {useCase.name} with a trigger that represents real intent, not a convenient automation event. For abandoned cart, distinguish cart from checkout and suppress people who purchased another variant. For replenishment, use product-specific timing rather than a universal delay. For winback, split one-time gift buyers from customers who once bought repeatedly. The email app should make those distinctions easy enough that the team can audit them before a sale.</p><p>The message sequence should add new information at each step. Email one handles the immediate objection: trust, product fit, checkout friction, delivery, or usage. Email two adds proof, comparison, education, or a softer incentive. Email three should only exist if it changes the decision; repeating the same coupon is usually a margin leak disguised as automation. Dynamic product blocks should be checked for availability, variant accuracy, and whether the product still matches the customer's original interest.</p><p>Measurement should be reviewed weekly for the first month. Track entries, conversions, unsubscribes, spam complaints, revenue per recipient, margin after discount, repeat purchase behavior, and overlap with campaigns. Pull a few real customer examples and ask whether the journey feels sensible. If the flow makes money but creates confusion, trains shoppers to wait for coupons, or contacts customers too soon after purchase, it needs adjustment rather than celebration.</p><h3>Common mistakes to avoid</h3><ul><li>Launching {useCase.name} without excluding recent purchasers and active support issues.</li><li>Using one incentive for first-time buyers, VIPs, gift buyers, and coupon-only shoppers.</li><li>Counting platform-attributed revenue without checking Shopify margin and order quality.</li><li>Letting the flow run through major sale periods without pause or priority rules.</li></ul></article></section>; })()}

