  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Operator evidence to collect before trusting {app.name}</h2><p>This {site.primaryKeyword} review should leave a retention owner with evidence, not vibes. Open Shopify and choose five real customer timelines: a new subscriber with no orders, a shopper who abandoned a high-value product, a recent first-time buyer, a repeat buyer who normally purchases on a predictable cycle, and a lapsed customer who once bought during a sale. Then test whether {app.name} can explain what each person should receive next and what they should be excluded from. If the answer depends on a spreadsheet, hidden tag, or agency-only convention, the app is weaker than the demo suggests.</p><p>For this site, the important surface area is subscriber capture, customer education, cart recovery, post-purchase timing, replenishment, winback, and deliverability. {app.name} earns a stronger score when those jobs live in one understandable operating rhythm. It loses points when it creates a prettier editor but leaves trigger accuracy, consent, product context, suppression, or reporting ambiguous. The practical question is whether a merchant can make a safe change on a busy Thursday before a launch without breaking another journey.</p><p>Ask the vendor to walk through a failure. Inventory is out of stock, a coupon is already attached, a customer purchased on another device, deliverability softened last week, and a campaign is scheduled for the same audience tomorrow. A serious email app makes the safe answer visible. A shallow tool still sends because the automation technically qualifies.</p><h3>Evidence checklist</h3><ul><li>Real Shopify customer examples match the intended journeys and exclusions.</li><li>Product, order, consent, discount, and customer-stage fields are visible where the marketer edits the workflow.</li><li>The team can name the