  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Deeper buying test for {a?.name} vs {b?.name}</h2><p>A useful comparison should simulate the next ninety days, not just compare menus. Build the same operating calendar in both tools: one acquisition capture path, one intent-recovery path, one customer education path, one repeat-purchase or reactivation path, and one high-pressure promotion. For each, document the trigger, audience, exclusion, offer, product context, channel coordination, reporting view, and owner. The winner is the tool that makes the calendar easier to run after the onboarding call ends.</p><p>Use {site.primaryKeyword} criteria instead of generic SaaS criteria. The deciding work is subscriber capture, customer education, cart recovery, post-purchase timing, replenishment, winback, and deliverability. If {a?.name} handles those jobs with fewer manual rules, it deserves the nod even if {b?.name} has a nicer campaign editor. If {b?.name} protects over-discounting the list or letting flows collide during launch weeks better, that matters more than one extra dashboard. Shopify teams do not need abstract power; they need safe changes, cleaner targeting, and revenue that survives margin math.</p><p>Do not let attribution settle the argument by itself. Compare the tools against repeat purchase rate, revenue per recipient, contribution margin after coupons, unsubscribe pressure, and deliverability movement. Also count team time: setup meetings, QA passes, segment cleanup, creative edits, agency dependency, support tickets, and the cost of fixing mistakes. A cheaper app can become expensive if every sale week requires manual audits. A powerful app can become expensive if nobody trusts the interface enough to keep improving flows.</p><h3>Decision notes to write down</h3><ul><li>Where {a?.name} is clearly safer or faster.</li><li>Where {b?.name} is clearly safer or faster.</li><li>Which customer moment is most valuable for this store right now.</li><li>What migration step would break revenue if rushed.</li></ul></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const useCase = USE_CASES.find((item) => item.slug === parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Advanced implementation notes for {useCase.name}</h2><p>{useCase.name} should start with a policy, not a template. Write the commercial rule first: who qualifies, why the message is useful now, what product or order context changes the copy, when the customer should be suppressed, and which other campaigns take priority. Then choose the email app that can express that policy without a tangle of manual tags.</p><p>For {site.primaryKeyword}, the hidden work is subscriber capture, customer education, cart recovery, post-purchase timing, replenishment, winback, and deliverability. A thin setup sends the same message to every eligible profile. A stronger setup changes timing and proof based on the customer: first-time versus repeat buyer, full-price versus coupon buyer, high-AOV versus low-margin cart, subscription versus one-off order, gift purchase versus self purchase, and recent support issue versus clean journey. These differences are where the revenue quality comes from.</p><p>Before launch, run a QA table with at least ten examples. Include recent purchasers, inactive subscribers, VIPs, discount-sensitive shoppers, customers with multiple carts, buyers whose product is out of stock, and people already scheduled for a campaign. Record the expected outcome and the actual outcome. If the app cannot explain a mismatch, fix the rule before sending. After launch, review repeat purchase rate, revenue per recipient, contribution margin after coupons, unsubscribe pressure, and deliverability movement and one or two customer timelines each week until the workflow behaves predictably.</p><h3>Common pitfalls</h3><ul><li>Launching {useCase.name} with a clever subject line but weak exclusions.</li><li>Letting attributed revenue hide over-discounting the list or letting flows collide during launch weeks.</li><li>Using one offer for every customer value band.</li><li>Failing to pause or adjust the workflow during launches, stockouts, holidays, and support spikes.</li></ul></article></section> })()}


