        <p>The migration note matters because Shopify retention systems usually fail at the edges. Consent timestamps disappear, old tags keep firing, product blocks show stale inventory, coupons stack, segment counts shift, and reporting changes make the new tool look better or worse than it really is. Keep the first rollout narrow enough that the team can inspect individual customer timelines. If the tool cannot explain why ten sample customers did or did not qualify, it is not ready for a broad launch.</p>
        <p>Finally, judge the page by whether it protects against coupon pressure, inbox placement, and post-purchase confusion. A tool can create attributed revenue while making the program less disciplined. A better choice should make restraint easier: suppress when the customer already bought, hold back when margin is weak, pause during stockouts, branch when lifecycle stage changes, and measure the behavior that continues after the campaign. That is the standard behind the recommendations here.</p>
